[1] Pernambuco State
Date: Tue 30 Jan 2018, 3:01 PM
Source: G1 [in Portuguese, machine trans., edited]
https://g1.globo.com/pe/pernambuco/noticia/secretaria-de-saude-investiga-tres-casos-de-botulismo-na-mesma-familia-em-pernambuco.ghtml


The Department of Health of Pernambuco investigated 3 cases of botulism in members of the same family, residents of Olinda, in Greater Recife. A 48 year old is hospitalized at Oswaldo Cruz University Hospital (Huoc), in the central area of the capital. He was admitted on [Thu 25 Jan 2018] with facial paralysis and difficulty swallowing. His parents, a 69-year-old man and a 65-year-old woman are also affected.

On [Tue 30 Jan 2018], the medical team of Oswaldo Cruz detailed the case during a press conference. According to the unit's infectious disease head, Demetrius Montenegro, the patient began to show classic symptoms of toxin action. "In this case, the problem is in the muscle of the face and in the neck area, which makes it difficult to swallow," he explained. Still according to the doctor, the patient is considered stable. Because of the difficulty of swallowing, he is fed through a tube but he is expected to be discharged from the Intensive Care Unit. Materials were collected with blood, gastric lavage and intestinal lavage of the patients. The samples were sent to the Adolfo Lutz Institute, in São Paulo, for epidemiological confirmation.

According to the State Department of Health, the patient's parents are hospitalized in a private hospital in Recife. Both had facial and lower limb paralysis. Still according to the briefcase, the health of the women is stable and showed improvement in limb movement. The man did not present improvement in the limbs, but his state of health is stable. It is not yet known what would have caused the disease.

According to SES, the two men received the anti-botulinum serum, which needs to be applied within 7 days after the onset of symptoms.

The State Department of Health said that the cases of the disease in Pernambuco are rare. There was 1 case of botulism in 2007 and 3 in 2016. In all of them, patients evolved well and without sequelae, according to the brief.

By means of a note, the State Department of Health reported that the technical team of the Pernambuco Agency of Sanitary Surveillance (Apevisa) was in the patients' home on [Mon 29 Jan 2018]. The visit was also attended by the Sanitary Surveillance of Olinda and the Epidemiological Surveillance of SES.

At the residence, the teams collected some food samples such as jerky, honey, kingdom cheese and pot-guava. The samples were sent for analysis at the Adolfo Lutz Institute in São Paulo to check for the presence of botulinum toxin.

[Byline: Thaiys Estarque]

